article.headline: Mavs (11-0) match franchise's best win streak
article.linkText: Mavs thrash punchless Lakers to go 11-0
article.story:
DALLAS (AP) -- The Mavericks and Lakers have played many ugly, lopsided games over the last decade. But never before has Dallas looked so good and Los Angeles so awful.
Finley

Nowitzki

Steve Nash had 21 points and Dirk Nowitzki scored seven of his 18 during a game-breaking run in the second quarter as the Mavericks improved to 11-0 by beating the Lakers 98-72 Tuesday night. Dallas matched the longest winning streak in its 23 seasons. "That's a tough thing to do, not just for our organization but for any team in the league,'' said Michael Finley, who had 18 points and a career-best 15 rebounds. "If you think about it, that's a lot of games. We're going to continue to build on it.'' Mavericks coach Don Nelson admitted he's "not thinking too much of this win'' because the Lakers were without Shaquille O'Neal, who averages 31.4 points and 12.1 rebounds against Dallas. Still, the Mavs did a nice job of capitalizing. Dallas beat Los Angeles for just the fifth time in 46 meetings since 1991. It was the Mavericks' most lopsided victory ever over the Lakers, topping a 23-point win in 1986, and they did it in historic fashion. Los Angeles' 30.8 shooting percentage (28-of-91) was its worst ever, and the lowest the Mavericks have ever held anyone. With owner Jerry Buss watching from the stands, the Lakers came within a basket of matching their al-time lowest point total, which was set just six games before. Los Angeles fell to 3-8, having lost two straight, six of seven and four in a row on the road. Coach Phil Jackson accused his team of not playing hard, and Kobe Bryant heartily agreed. "I look around the locker room and I don't see fire in anybody's eyes,'' said Bryant, who led Los Angeles with 18 points but was only 7-of-21. "Everybody is kind of dozing off a little bit. There's no intensity.'' Jackson and Bryant were complimentary of the Mavericks, but also said things would've been different with O'Neal. "Teams know that what goes around comes around,'' Bryant said. "We're not going anywhere. They know that. We usually get the last laugh.'' O'Neal is expected to return Friday against Chicago. He should be rounding into form by the time the Mavericks visit the Staples Center on Dec. 6. "Dallas has been beating up a lot of teams,'' Jackson said. "They can have their fun because we're going to be back together in another month.'' Remaining the only unbeaten team in the NBA, Dallas tied the sixth-best start in league history. The Mavericks will try to keep climbing the chart with home games Thursday against Houston and Saturday against Seattle. The record is 15-0 by the Rockets in 1993-94 and Washington in 1948-49. Dallas' previous best start to a season was 4-0. The only other time the Mavs have won 11 in a row was in February-March 1988. Nash scored 17 in the first half, when Dallas led by as many as 15. Finley stretched the lead to 27 with a 3-pointer midway through the third quarter and the lead peaked at 28. Nowitzki tied his season-best with 17 rebounds and Shawn Bradley had a season-best 16 points and 12 rebounds. Dallas has won 21 straight over the last three seasons when he records a double-double. "We took care of business,'' Nowitzki said. Los Angeles led 25-23 on a dunk by Bryant with 0.8 seconds left in the first quarter. But a silly foul by Derek Fisher on the inbounds pass let Nash hit two free throws to tie it. The Lakers never led again. Dallas scored the first six points of the second quarter, then went on a 14-2 run. The Lakers played so badly that at times they looked like the mid-90s Mavericks. And Bryant was as much to blame as anyone. He had an airball on his first shot of the game and another during a third quarter he probably wants to forget. His period also included a technical foul, missing a technical foul shot, throwing a ball out of bounds right after he stole it and blowing a 3-on-1 layup following a backcourt steal. He shouldn't feel too bad about that last one. After all, Rick Fox missed two chances to tip it in.

Game notes
Four teams have started 11-0: The Hawks and Lakers in '97-98, Portland in 1990-91 and Boston in 1964-65. ... Officials used replay to verify Fisher's foul on Nash at the end of the first quarter. ... The Lakers had only 10 players available. Devean George has tendinitis in his right ankle and Soumaila Samake served the fourth game of a five-game suspension. ... Mavs backup center Evan Eschmeyer had arthroscopic surgery to repair damaged cartilage in his right knee Tuesday and will be out four-to- six weeks.
